<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
These sentence patterns indicate a change from one state into another. The verbs used express possibility or ability
(for example, potential verbs).
The form which uses @Vru{{}} means that something which could not be done now can be done. 

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{yatto@KJ{{oneself^revolve^car}}ni@KJ{{ride}}reru@EM{{youninarimashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I've finally become able to ride a bicycle.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The form with @Vnai{{}} indicates that something which previously could be done can now no longer be done.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{grove}}:hayashi}}sanha@KJ{{sake}}wo@KJ{{drink}}manai@EM{{youninarimashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Hayashi doesn't drink <em>sake</e> any more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In the case that @Vnai{{}} is used to indicate that something can no longer be done, the change must have happened gradually. If the change was sudden then @HI{{nakunaru}} must be used instead.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{grove}}:hayashi}}sanha@KJ{{sake}}wo@KJ{{drink}}manai@EM{{youninakunatta}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Hayashi doesn't drink <em>sake</e> any more. <em>(This change happened rapidly.</em>)
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The form @HI{{@EM{{youninatteiru}}}} emphasises that the current state has come about after a long process.
</p>

